"reviewcomment":"Who could resist the aroma of a freshly bake dough coming out from the oven and not getting hold of them? The sight of it was enough to make me hyperventilate, let alone tasting one.<br><br>It as probably 6-months ago since I last had my bun from Maison Kayser at Scotts Square. They have never failed to draw crowds despite the fact that they are anchoring at the basement of a smaller but prestigious mall. Prior to its opening last December, it was one of the most anticipated bakery by many eager Singaporeans. I admitted being one - so sheepish.<br><br>Their butter croissant has always be a big draw. As they baked in batches to allow the bread to taste its best (given the high humidity level in Singapore, the crust gets softened pretty fast), luck plays a big part in determining if I manage to bring one home today. It was far better than striking lottery, to me.<br><br>Today, I am not in my lady luck - I missed the batch of croissants. The fella who has gotten the last piece, must be gloating now. Not feeling worst, I have still have other consolations to pick from.<br><br>Recalling what I had on my last two visits, I chose an array of sweet bread which tasted almost new to me.<br><br>Pain Aux Pommes - The bun had a very faint sweetness arising from the honey. Its shell was undeniably crusty with a chewy dough. It was visibly filled with large apple chunks, stodgy and a tad sour. The walnut adds a good nutty flavor to the rustic bun.<br><br>The Orange - Not sure if I read the tag correctly at the counter, &#34;earl grey with orange peels&#34;. I sniffed none of the earl grey scent but the bread was baked using dark rye flour - nutty and doughy. I have always been attracted to chewy European-styled bread; this was the show stopper among all, which I bagged today. Generous amount of orange peels were seen everywhere, candied but still contained its natural citrus flavor. Marvelous!<br><br>Pain Aux Yuzu - Didn&#39;t know that I had this yuzu bun until I read my previous blog! So this was my second attempt? And it had the same consistency! I adored the crumble yet the center was soft. The sweetness in the dough was prominent but natural. The yuzu peels were seen scattered evenly which gave a good lemony taste. I am still loving it.",
