"rating":"4.5",
"reviewcomment":"Fish soup is such a comfort food for me, and I had to try the ABC market&#39;s resident fish soup. The queue was pretty long, and right in the shop there worked a feisty, skinny uncle. With one hand, throwing fresh fish and fish heads into old-school metallic pots that rested on flaming stoves, he took orders with gusto and energy. I had a good feeling this would be a good choice, and decided to go for their fish soup with chu mifen. The soup was milky and slightly sweet, exactly how I liked it. The fish was very fresh, and didn&#39;t crumble despite being in the soup for a while. The garnish really upped the flavour factor of the dish, and the amount of vegetables in the soup also made it healthier (and easier for my conscience to stomach). I&#39;d return to this stall in a heartbeat! The bowl cost me $3.50, which is quite cheap considering that the average price at shopping mall food courts can go up to $5 or $5.50. But most of all, it&#39;s the uncle&#39;s attitude to serving his customers that wins me over. Polite, patient, and willing to converse with customers.",
